      Bed Bath & Beyond: beyond=C2=A0bankruptcy
   =20
 =20

At some point in, let=E2=80=99s say, January, Bed Bath & Beyond Inc.  was n=
o longer a viable business. It was losing money, it had a lot of debt, it w=
as in default on that debt and couldn=E2=80=99t pay. It looked around for s=
omebody to buy the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0in or out of bankruptcy =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and continue operating its stores, but it couldn=E2=80=99t find anyon=
e. It prepared to file for bankruptcy, with a plan to liquidate the invento=
ry, sell what it could, and give its creditors whatever was left, which wou=
ld be a fraction of what it owed them.
And then somebody had the bright idea of, hey, why not=C2=A0sell a bunch of=
 stock? Bed Bath was a meme stock, retail investors liked it, and Bed Bath =
could sell stock to them to raise cash to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, to hand over=
 to the creditors. It couldn=E2=80=99t sell stock to raise enough money to =
fix its problems and become a functional business again; that would require=
 too much cash, and any cash that it did raise, it was contractually requir=
ed to hand directly to its creditors. But if it sold a lot of stock, it wou=
ld have some more cash to hand to the creditors. At this point in its life =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the all-but-bankruptcy part of its life =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bed B=
ath was pretty much in the business of maximizing recovery for its creditor=
s, and selling stock was a way to do that.
  [3]

And so it went out to sell worthless stock in a business that was no longer=
 viable, to retail investors who did not realize that the stock was worthle=
ss and the business was no longer viable. To be fair, Bed Bath did=C2=A0tel=
l=C2=A0them. If a company wants to sell stock, it has to put out a prospect=
us with disclosure about its business, and Bed Bath did, and the prospectus=
 very much included phrases like =E2=80=9Cthe Company expects that it will =
likely file for bankruptcy protection=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cour equity hold=
ers would likely not receive any recovery at all in a bankruptcy scenario.=
=E2=80=9D
But two facts about=C2=A0meme-stock retail investors are (1) they ain=E2=80=
=99t reading all that and (2) they are always hopeful, so Bed Bath managed =
to raise several hundred million dollars in a series of stock offerings.=C2=
=A0Then it  filed for bankruptcy last month, with, still, a plan to liquida=
te its assets and return what was left to creditors. It estimated that the =
liquidation would raise about $718 million, to pay back about $1.8 billion =
of debt, so the several hundred million dollars that it raised from the sto=
ck market was a big help. For the creditors. Not for the shareholders, obvi=
ously. They are getting zero.
Look! This is all debatable! What do I know? In January, Bed Bath did not k=
now=C2=A0that it was no longer viable, and I do not=C2=A0know=C2=A0that now=
. It is in bankruptcy, but it has not liquidated everything yet. There is a=
lways some optionality, some chance that the business will recover in such =
a way that the company is viable and the stock is valuable. =E2=80=9CBed Ba=
th & Beyond has pulled off long shot transactions several times in the last=
 six months, so nobody should think Bed Bath & Beyond will not be able to d=
o so again,=E2=80=9D it said in its bankruptcy declaration.=C2=A0Maybe it w=
ill discover a $5 billion stash of diamonds in one of its stores and say =
=E2=80=9Chey, we=E2=80=99re rich now, no need to liquidate, let=E2=80=99s p=
ay back all our debt, refresh our inventory and get back to selling housewa=
res.=E2=80=9D Or maybe Elon Musk will put in a bid to buy it just for giggl=
es, and then somehow be forced to follow through.=C2=A0And then the stock w=
ill be worth a lot, and the people who bought it for $0.30 in April will ma=
ke a fortune. I do not expect this outcome, but  I have been wrong before, =
and it is not, like, a physical impossibility.
Still I mean I have read the bankruptcy filings. Then there is this:

Passionate fans think Bed Bath & Beyond stock isn=E2=80=99t dead yet.=C2=A0
Investors in meme stocks are typically eternal optimists, wagering on stock=
s they are excited about even if the underlying fundamentals are weak. Even=
 in that world, the Bed Bath & Beyond bet is extreme. The company has said =
it expects shareholders will be wiped out, a projection that emphasizes the=
 hard math of its chapter 11 filing.
=E2=80=9CIt is obviously the ultimate form of speculation, with buyers bett=
ing on the success of a reorganization on a worthless stock,=E2=80=9D said =
Charles Geisst, a retired professor of finance at Manhattan College.
The stock now trades for pennies in the over-the-counter market, the provin=
ce of companies that generally can=E2=80=99t trade on regular exchanges. Si=
nce it started trading on May 3, Bed Bath & Beyond stock has made up more t=
han 9% of trades in the Pink Current Market, the over-the-counter market in=
 which it resides, according to data from OTC Markets Group as of Friday.=
=C2=A0=E2=80=A6
Michael =E2=80=9CJared=E2=80=9D Martin, 25, said that most of his portfolio=
 is tied up in shares of Bed Bath & Beyond and GameStop. When he received a=
 bonus check from his IT job, he said he poured much of it into the retaile=
r=E2=80=99s shares this March. He doesn=E2=80=99t plan to sell.
=E2=80=9CI think that Bed Bath & Beyond, even in bankruptcy, is one of the =
best deals in the stock market,=E2=80=9D said Martin, who is based near Lou=
isville, Ky.
Martin, who started chatting with other traders on the Reddit forum WallStr=
eetBets years ago, first got into the stock around the time that the billio=
naire investor Ryan Cohen did so last year.=C2=A0
Martin has gradually increased his stake, while doing hours of analysis on =
the company and how it might exit bankruptcy. =E2=80=9CYou can call me a co=
nspiracy theorist,=E2=80=9D he said.=C2=A0

As far as I can tell, Bed Bath kept selling stock until very close to the t=
ime it filed for bankruptcy. I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0assume =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0has =E2=80=A6=C2=A0stopped? When Hertz Global Holdings Inc. dec=
ided to sell stock to retail investors=C2=A0while in bankruptcy, it  asked =
the bankruptcy court for permission first; the bankruptcy court was like =
=E2=80=9Csure I guess, this is nuts but good for creditors so go ahead.=E2=
=80=9D (The US Securities and Exchange Commission quickly  shut it down tho=
ugh.) I assume that Bed Bath has not asked for permission to keep selling s=
tock because it is not still selling stock. But, you know. Somebody is buyi=
ng it! It trades several million dollars a day, and the price is up more th=
an 100% since its lows of early May. If Bed Bath captured, like, 20% of tha=
t volume, by selling more stock in a public at-the-market offering, that wo=
uld raise enough money to put a dent in its legal bills anyway. Bankruptcy =
is expensive, retail traders want to give someone money to buy Bed Bath sto=
ck, why shouldn=E2=80=99t the company take that money to spend on its bankr=
uptcy?
Oh, reasons, sure, but honestly not=C2=A0that=C2=A0much has changed since B=
ed Bath last sold stock to retail investors. When it sold stock in April, t=
hings were pretty hopeless, and it warned buyers that it would probably go =
bankrupt and their stock would be worthless. Now it is May, things remain p=
retty hopeless, Bed Bath is=C2=A0in=C2=A0bankruptcy, the stock sure looks w=
orthless, but people are still buying it. Before it filed for bankruptcy, B=
ed Bath was pretty ruthless about taking advantage of that demand. Why stop=
 with bankruptcy?
Why stop with anything? Eventually Bed Bath=E2=80=99s bankruptcy will concl=
ude. Current expectations are that it will conclude with liquidating the as=
sets and cashing out the creditors at some fraction of what they are owed. =
But why not leave the corporate shell around, let its stock keep trading, l=
et it keep selling stock, and send the proceeds to creditors? Give creditor=
s cash now, plus a residual stream of quarterly payments from stock investo=
rs, just a little tax on people who want to keep trading Bed Bath stock lon=
g after it stops making sense. Somebody somewhere will have a conspiracy th=
eory about Bed Bath=E2=80=99s revival that can survive the end of the bankr=
uptcy case. Part of the value of Bed Bath & Beyond is that it is a meme sto=
ck with=C2=A0retail shareholders whom=C2=A0harsh economic reality cannot de=
ter from buying the stock. That value belongs to the creditors now!=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      AT1 reforms
   =20
 =20

A tension in bank regulation is that you want people to buy the equity of b=
anks, so that banks have lots of capital to absorb losses in a crisis so th=
ey don=E2=80=99t lose depositor money or require government bailouts. When =
there is a bank failure, you will want the equity to absorb losses: That is=
 what it is there for, and better for equity investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0who w=
ere consciously taking risk buying the bank=E2=80=99s stock, and expected t=
o do well if the bank did well and to lose everything if it went bust =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to lose money than for depositors or taxpayers to lose money.
But bank failures tend to come in waves, and you will want=C2=A0other=C2=A0=
banks to be able to raise lots of equity easily to shore up confidence in t=
he system and make their failure less likely. And if the equity of=C2=A0thi=
s=C2=A0bank absorbs too many losses, people won=E2=80=99t want to buy stock=
 in=C2=A0other=C2=A0banks, because they will notice how risky bank stocks a=
re. And then the other banks won=E2=80=99t be able to raise capital, and th=
e crisis will continue. We have seen a bit of this with US regional banks: =
Several banks were briskly seized and had their equity written down to zero=
, and the result is that other   regional bank stocks got crushed. And so w=
hile lots of regional banks could probably use more equity, nobody is about=
 to go out and do a stock offering.
The exact same analysis applies to other bank capital securities. Additiona=
l tier 1 capital securities, for instance, which are perpetual-ish debt-ish=
 securities that pay a high interest rate but get crushed if the bank fails=
, are designed to absorb losses. If a bank fails, it is good and right for =
them to absorb losses. But, though it says right on the tin that they absor=
b losses, and though they pay a high interest rate in compensation for the =
risk that investors are taking, they are not=C2=A0really=C2=A0bought by ris=
k-seeking gamblers. They are bought by fixed-income funds and high-net-wort=
h investors who want steady income. When an AT1 gets written down to zero, =
those investors stop buying all the=C2=A0other=C2=A0AT1s. And that makes=C2=
=A0other=C2=A0banks riskier: They can=E2=80=99t raise as much loss-absorbin=
g capital, or they can but they have to pay more for it.=C2=A0
In some rough sense, the ideal way for a bank capital instrument=C2=A0to wo=
rk would be:
=09People buy it thinking that it can never lose money.=09If the bank fails=
, it goes to zero to absorb losses.

There are second-order effects, and this is not really right. If people rea=
lly think they can=E2=80=99t lose money on bank AT1s, then ordinary people =
will put their life savings in bank AT1s, businesses will put their payroll=
 in bank AT1s, and writing down bank AT1s will have huge consequences for t=
he economy. Still it is=C2=A0kind=C2=A0of right. You want the people who=C2=
=A0can=C2=A0bear the risk of bank failures to=C2=A0want=C2=A0to bear the ri=
sk, and then, when a bank fails, you want them to actually bear the risk.
Anyway, Credit Suisse Group AG failed in March,   its AT1 securities were w=
ritten down to zero, people have been hopping mad ever since, and European =
bank regulators have taken pains to say =E2=80=9Coh=C2=A0we=C2=A0would neve=
r do that, AT1s are totally safe, why would they absorb losses?=E2=80=9D Bl=
oomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0  Abhinav Ramnarayan and Steven Arons report:

The European Banking Authority has been holding talks on ways to boost inve=
stor interest in the AT1 market after Switzerland=E2=80=99s shock decision =
to wipe out about $17 billion of Credit Suisse Group AG notes.
The EBA earlier this month addressed ideas such as a ban on banks paying di=
vidends before they consider skipping an AT1 coupon to preserve capital dur=
ing times of stress, people familiar with the matter said, asking not to be=
 identified discussing the private information. Other ideas floated at an e=
vent held by the body included a requirement to pay out skipped AT1 coupons=
 at a later stage rather than allowing them to be canceled altogether, the =
people said. =E2=80=A6
The price of issuing AT1 bonds is still elevated compared with levels befor=
e the Credit Suisse rescue. Their average yield in an index of European AT1=
 debt is currently above 11% =E2=80=94 almost twice the average coupon of r=
oughly 6% on previously issued AT1 bonds, according to data compiled by Blo=
omberg.

These changes would make AT1s=C2=A0less loss-absorbing, which would be bad =
for their usefulness as bank capital, but=C2=A0more attractive to investors=
, and if nobody buys them then they=E2=80=99re not that useful anyway.
Incidentally my own view of the correct regulatory response here is somethi=
ng like =E2=80=9Cmemories in financial markets are extremely short, and any=
 time a bond investor indignantly huffs that she will never buy some type o=
f bond again, she=E2=80=99ll be buying it within a week.=E2=80=9D You have =
a meeting with AT1 investors, they say =E2=80=9Cyou need to make sure that =
these bonds can never lose money,=E2=80=9D you nod and say =E2=80=9Cof cour=
se, of course,=E2=80=9D you wait six minutes, you forget all about it. I am=
 not sure that will work here but I don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99d bet aga=
inst it.

 =20
   =20
      Elsewhere in Credit Suisse AT1s
   =20
 =20

When Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s additional tier 1 capital securities were zero=
ed in March, its subordinated bonds were not. The subordinated bonds were f=
ine, they are still outstanding, and Credit Suisse (which is being acquired=
 by UBS Group AG) is still paying them. Intuitively, the way to describe th=
is is something like =E2=80=9Cthe subordinated bonds are senior to the AT1s=
, so the subordinated bonds get paid before the AT1s do.=E2=80=9D And in fa=
ct it was and is fairly standard to describe the capital structure of Credi=
t Suisse =E2=80=94=C2=A0or any other big European bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0by sa=
ying that AT1s are below subordinated bonds, which are below senior unsecur=
ed bonds, etc.
There are credit default swaps outstanding on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s subor=
dinated bonds. These swaps would be triggered, and would pay off, if the su=
bordinated bonds were written down, but those bonds were not written down. =
They would also be triggered, though, if any Credit Suisse bonds that are =
=E2=80=9Cnot subordinated to=E2=80=9D those bonds were written down. The AT=
1s were written down. Were the AT1s =E2=80=9Cnot subordinated to=E2=80=9D t=
he subordinated bonds? Obviously they were subordinated, in a practical=C2=
=A0sense =E2=80=94 they were written down and the bonds were not!=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but the documents are a little ambiguous and these things thriv=
e on technicalities, so some hedge funds bought CDS on the sub bonds and   =
claimed it was triggered.=C2=A0Today they lost:

A panel tasked with overseeing the credit default swaps market has ruled th=
at the write down of=C2=A0Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s Additional Tier =
1 notes will not trigger an insurance payout.=C2=A0
The Credit Derivatives Determinations Committee (CDDC) determined at a meet=
ing on Wednesday that the write down would not lead to a payout of the defa=
ult swaps tied to the bank=E2=80=99s subordinated debt, according to a=C2=
=A0notice=C2=A0on its website. In reaching its decision, the committee took=
 the view that the AT1 notes were in fact junior to the subordinated bonds =
underlying the swaps.

Of course, but weirder things have happened and it was worth a shot.

 =20
   =20
      Going Infinite
   =20
 =20

One thing that I have found, in writing about finance for a long time, is t=
hat financial scandals, crimes and disasters are more fun=C2=A0to write abo=
ut than stuff going well. Part of this is that the scandals often have stak=
es and drama, while everything going fine does not. Part of it is that much=
 of normal finance is=C2=A0secretive =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you have a good inve=
stment strategy or product you are not necessarily going to explain how it =
works =E2=80=94=C2=A0while the scandals tend to produce lots of public info=
rmation, in the form of court filings. Part of it is that the scandals are =
often pretty funny;=C2=A0frauds tend to play on interesting quirks of human=
 nature and financial markets, and also the people doing the fraud often se=
nd=C2=A0each other entertaining=C2=A0emails about it.
And so, when some big financial scandal happens, am I a bit gleeful? I am. =
Do I feel bad for the people who have lost their life savings in the fraud,=
 and the people who might go to prison for doing it? I do. But I am gleeful=
 for=C2=A0me.
Anyway here is an interview with Michael Lewis, who has a new book coming o=
ut about Sam Bankman-Fried and the collapse of FTX. Lewis was spending a lo=
t of time with Bankman-Fried back when he was just a financial=C2=A0success=
=C2=A0story, a young self-made billionaire who was creating the future of f=
inance. And then Bankman-Fried=C2=A0became a huge scandal, which worked out=
 even better for Lewis:

When he was arrested, did you worry that it might blow up your book, or mak=
e it better?
I hate to say this. It=E2=80=99s horrible. It does not reflect well on me a=
s a human being, but my first thought was, =E2=80=98Oh my God=E2=80=99 =E2=
=80=94 it was like a lock clicking into place =E2=80=94 =E2=80=98now I have=
 the story.=E2=80=99 It didn=E2=80=99t occur to me for a moment that it wou=
ld blow up the book. I did think, just how messy is this going to get, as t=
he writer, because I=E2=80=99d been so involved. Nobody watched this the wa=
y I did, so, was I going to be dragged into this in some way? But I=E2=80=
=99ve been allowed to do my job, and it=E2=80=99s been one of the most exci=
ting creative experiences I=E2=80=99ve ever had.
You=E2=80=99ve continued to visit Bankman-Fried. How has his legal situatio=
n affected your access to him, and do you feel he=E2=80=99s more guarded in=
 his conversations with you?
He=E2=80=99s the ideal subject. He=E2=80=99s locked up in his house an hour=
 from my house with an ankle monitor. He can=E2=80=99t go anywhere. It=E2=
=80=99s unbelievably convenient, as long as they keep him there. So, as lon=
g as he welcomes me into the house, it=E2=80=99s fine. I=E2=80=99ve been se=
eing him roughly every two weeks.

He=E2=80=99s not wrong.

 =20
   =20
      Salad robots
   =20
 =20

In 10 years, do you think it is more likely that the food service industry =
will have been entirely replaced by robots, or the financial services indus=
try?
  [4]
 At Bloomberg Businessweek, Elizabeth Dunn reports from Sweetgreen=E2=80=99=
s  secret salad robot lab:

A small team of engineers is on-site here in the Chicago suburb of Napervil=
le, working out any last-minute kinks in the automated assembly line. Micha=
el Farid, one of the Infinite Kitchen=E2=80=99s inventors, is excited to sh=
ow off what it can do. He keys in an order for a spring asparagus salad on =
one of the restaurant=E2=80=99s touchscreen tablets. In front of us, a comp=
ostable bowl whizzes forward along a track, pausing beneath a series of cle=
ar plastic tubes that call to mind bulk candy dispensers, except they=E2=80=
=99re filled with arugula and lentils and beets. The bowl rotates as ingred=
ients drop inside=E2=80=94in engineering-speak, this is a =E2=80=9Ctwo degr=
ees of freedom plating system,=E2=80=9D but imagine a salad bowl doing piro=
uettes=E2=80=94ensuring that they=E2=80=99re all arranged neatly, just like=
 in the photos.
The exact dispensing mechanism is a matter of strict secrecy, and I=E2=80=
=99ve sworn to take what I=E2=80=99m seeing inside the Infinite Kitchen to =
my grave. The upshot is that it can serve up most of Sweetgreen=E2=80=99s 5=
0-odd ingredients, everything from hardboiled eggs to shredded cabbage to d=
elicate cheeses. At the end of the line, an aproned employee adds any items=
 the robots can=E2=80=99t handle, such as herbs and a side of dressing, the=
n gives the order a final once-over and places it on a pickup shelf. =E2=80=
=9CI would say our portioning system is a version six or seven at this poin=
t,=E2=80=9D Farid says. =E2=80=9CWe used to joke that if our whole menu was=
 edamame, this would be so much easier.=E2=80=9D

It does kind of feel like, in terms of difficulty for robots, synthesizing =
and analyzing all of human knowledge to predict the future of financial mar=
kets might be easier than gently distributing delicate cheeses. They=E2=80=
=99re getting there with the cheeses.

