<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FDIC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of this spring=E2=80=99s=C2=A0US regiona=
l banking crisis can be explained this way:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks bought a lot of=C2=A0Treasury b=
onds and other US government-backed securities when interest rates were low=
, paying roughly 100 cents on the dollar for them.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">Interest rates went up a lot, driving the prices of those =
bonds=C2=A0down to, say, 85 cents on the dollar.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Banks had big losses on those bonds, eating through a lot of=
 their capital.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People noticed, st=
ocks went down, deposits fled, some banks failed and others have looked sha=
ky.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One solution to this crisis would be that, if =
the bonds magically went back to being worth 100 cents on the dollar, the b=
anks would mostly be fine again.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That seems improbable, though=C2=A0I guess one interesting=C2=A0m=
echanism=C2=A0would be if the banking crisis caused enough of a recession t=
o drive long-term interest rates back to where they were in 2020.=C2=A0Then=
<em>=C2=A0</em>the <em>bonds</em> would be fine, though probably the banks =
would have credit losses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another solution to this crisis would be that,=
 if the US government just=C2=A0<em>bought=C2=A0</em>the bonds from the ban=
ks at 100 cents on the dollar, the banks would mostly be fine again. Of cou=
rse then the government would have paid 100 cents for stuff worth 85 cents,=
 which seems bad. But through the magic of held-to-maturity accounting, you=
 can sort of wave your hands and pretend that it=E2=80=99s not bad. If the =
government paid 100 cents today for a bond worth 85 cents, and then held it=
 until it matured, it would get back 100 cents. (Plus interest, though not =
very much.) In some accounting sense, the government would not lose any mon=
ey: It would get a below-market rate of interest on its money for the next =
few years, but it would technically get all of its money back.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact this is kind of how the banks thou=
ght of these bonds: They were often in the banks=E2=80=99 held-to-maturity =
portfolios, meaning that they didn=E2=80=99t need to be marked down when th=
ey lost value due to changing interest rates. It=E2=80=99s just that, when =
people notice this stuff and deposits flee, you=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0</em>hold the bonds to maturity, because you have to sell them, at a los=
s,=C2=A0to pay back depositors. But the government is not funded by short-t=
erm deposits, so it really=C2=A0<em>can</em> hold the bonds to maturity.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact this is kind of, a little bit, <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31513959.263431/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNv=
dWxkbi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZmVkLWNhbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE3MjN=
fTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdG=
VybT0yMzA1MTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2aad=
2fba" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">a solution that the government hit on</a>: In response to the=
 failure of Silicon Valley Bank, the US Federal Reserve announced a new Ban=
k Term Funding Program that would=C2=A0<em>lend=C2=A0</em>the banks 100 cen=
ts on the dollar against bonds worth 85 cents on the dollar. This is not th=
e same thing as=C2=A0<em>buying=C2=A0</em>the bonds at 100 cents on the dol=
lar =E2=80=94=C2=A0the banks, rather than the government, are still economi=
cally on the hook for the losses =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is motivated by the =
same sort of thinking. =E2=80=9CEventually these bonds=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0<=
/em>pay out 100 cents on the dollar, so it=E2=80=99s fine to lend 100 cents=
 on the dollar against them, even if they are worth 85 cents today.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But nobody has=C2=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em>emb=
raced a program of =E2=80=9Cthe government will just buy the bonds back at =
par to make the banks healthy again,=E2=80=9D because it is kind of an extr=
eme=C2=A0transfer of losses from banks to taxpayers, even if you can wave y=
our hands a bit and pretend it isn=E2=80=99t.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31513959.263431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9saXZlY292ZXJhZ2Uvc3Rv=
Y2stbWFya2V0LXRvZGF5LWRvdy1qb25lcy0wNS0xNy0yMDIzL2NhcmQvYmFua3MtZXhwbG9yZS1=
nYW1iaXQtdG8tcmVwbGVuaXNoLWZkaWMtaW5zdXJhbmNlLWZ1bmQtODVUdnRDazZEaDJiaXJmN1=
hiSTc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBed86d775" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this from Andrew Ackerm=
an at the Wall Street Journal</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks have spent the past week or so testing w=
hat would be a clever gambit: Paying billions of dollars they collectively =
owe to replenish a federal deposit insurance fund using Treasurys instead o=
f cash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea=E2=80=94floated to regulators and law=
makers by PNC Financial Services Group and supported by others=E2=80=94coul=
d allow banks to take securities that are currently worth, say, 90 cents on=
 the dollar, and give them to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. at full p=
rice. That would effectively shift losses clogging the banks=E2=80=99 balan=
ce sheets to the FDIC, according to people familiar with the proposal. ...<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Proponents say nothing in the law says FDIC fe=
es have to be paid in cash, so the agency could change its rules. They say =
the move, if greenlighted by the FDIC, would help the banking system addres=
s the way rising rates over the past year have saddled lenders with billion=
s in losses on their portfolios of bonds. Those losses helped sink Silicon =
Valley Bank in March, sparking turmoil across the banking sector. =E2=80=A6=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Supporters say the government would hold the s=
ecurities until maturity, allowing them to recover principal and interest o=
n the debt. The government would suffer no losses, they say.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The FDIC has spent billions of dollars on its =
bank rescues =E2=80=94=C2=A0which is also a transfer of losses from banks t=
o the government <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
1513959.263431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjMtMDUtMTAvY29tcGFuaWVzLWFyZS1hbGxvd2VkLXRvLWRvLWJhZC1tZXJnZXJzP2NtcGlkPUJ=
CRDA1MTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dG=
VyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB37a0752b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> to make the banking system more solvent</a>=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is getting the money back by <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31513959.263431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmRpYy5nb3=
YvbmV3cy9wcmVzcy1yZWxlYXNlcy8yMDIzL3ByMjMwMzcuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB10bdfb53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">charging a special assessment to be paid by about 113 =
big=C2=A0=C2=A0banks</a>. If the banks pay the assessment with Treasuries t=
hat are worth 90 cents on the dollar, but that count for 100 cents on the d=
ollar, then they get a little discount on the assessment=C2=A0and<em>=C2=A0=
</em>get to move unpleasant assets off their balance sheets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why stop there? They should pay their taxes in=
 Treasuries. Really what they should do is pay executive bonuses in Treasur=
ies: =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re giving you a $1 million bonus, technically it i=
s only worth $850,000 but if you hold it to maturity it=E2=80=99s a million=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
