<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond: beyond=C2=A0bankruptcy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point in, let=E2=80=99s say, January, =
Bed Bath &amp; Beyond Inc. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/31513959.263431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjQvYmVkLWJhdGgtbW92ZXMtaW50by10aGUtYmV5b25kP2NtcGlkPUJCR=
DA1MTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy=
JnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBbab795d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> was no longer a viable business</a>. It was losing =
money, it had a lot of debt, it was in default on that debt and couldn=E2=
=80=99t pay. It looked around for somebody to buy the company =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in or out of bankruptcy =E2=80=94=C2=A0and continue operating its stores=
, but it couldn=E2=80=99t find anyone. It prepared to file for bankruptcy, =
with a plan to liquidate the inventory, sell what it could, and give its cr=
editors whatever was left, which would be a fraction of what it owed them.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then somebody had the bright idea of, hey,=
 why not=C2=A0<em>sell a bunch of stock</em>? Bed Bath was a meme stock, re=
tail investors liked it, and Bed Bath could sell stock to them to raise cas=
h to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, to hand over to the creditors. It couldn=E2=80=99=
t sell stock to raise enough money to fix its problems and become a functio=
nal business again; that would require too much cash, and any cash that it =
did raise, it was contractually required to hand directly to its creditors.=
 But if it sold a lot of stock, it would have some more cash to hand to the=
 creditors. At this point in its life =E2=80=94=C2=A0the all-but-bankruptcy=
 part of its life =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bed Bath was pretty much in the business o=
f maximizing recovery for its creditors, and selling stock was a way to do =
that.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so it went out to sell worthless stock in =
a business that was no longer viable, to retail investors who did not reali=
ze that the stock was worthless and the business was no longer viable. To b=
e fair, Bed Bath did=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>them. If a company wants to se=
ll stock, it has to put out a prospectus with disclosure about its business=
