<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A tension in bank regulation is that you want =
people to buy the equity of banks, so that banks have lots of capital to ab=
sorb losses in a crisis so they don=E2=80=99t lose depositor money or requi=
re government bailouts. When there is a bank failure, you will want the equ=
ity to absorb losses: That is what it is there for, and better for equity i=
nvestors =E2=80=94=C2=A0who were consciously taking risk buying the bank=E2=
=80=99s stock, and expected to do well if the bank did well and to lose eve=
rything if it went bust =E2=80=94=C2=A0to lose money than for depositors or=
 taxpayers to lose money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But bank failures tend to come in waves, and y=
ou will want=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>banks to be able to raise lots of equ=
ity easily to shore up confidence in the system and make their failure less=
 likely. And if the equity of=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>bank absorbs too many=
 losses, people won=E2=80=99t want to buy stock in=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em=
>banks, because they will notice how risky bank stocks are. And then the ot=
her banks won=E2=80=99t be able to raise capital, and the crisis will conti=
nue. We have seen a bit of this with US regional banks: Several banks were =
briskly seized and had their equity written down to zero, and the result is=
 that other <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/315139=
59.263431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtM=
DUtMDUvYmFuay1zdG9ja3MtbG9vay13b3JzZS10aGFuLWJhbmtzLWRvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTcy=
M19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV9=
0ZXJtPTIzMDUxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB03=
f2986a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  regional bank stocks got crushed</a>. And so while lots o=
f regional banks could probably use more equity, nobody is about to go out =
and do a stock offering.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The exact same analysis applies to other bank =
capital securities. Additional tier 1 capital securities, for instance, whi=
ch are perpetual-ish debt-ish securities that pay a high interest rate but =
get crushed if the bank fails, are designed to absorb losses. If a bank fai=
ls, it is good and right for them to absorb losses. But, though it says rig=
ht on the tin that they absorb losses, and though they pay a high interest =
rate in compensation for the risk that investors are taking, they are not=
=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>bought by risk-seeking gamblers. They are bought=
 by fixed-income funds and high-net-worth investors who want steady income.=
 When an AT1 gets written down to zero, those investors stop buying all the=
=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>AT1s. And that makes=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>ban=
ks riskier: They can=E2=80=99t raise as much loss-absorbing capital, or the=
y can but they have to pay more for it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some rough sense, the ideal way for a bank =
capital instrument=C2=A0to work would be:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People buy it thinking that it can nev=
er lose money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the bank fails, =
it goes to zero to absorb losses.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are second-order effects, and this is no=
t really right. If people really think they can=E2=80=99t lose money on ban=
k AT1s, then ordinary people will put their life savings in bank AT1s, busi=
nesses will put their payroll in bank AT1s, and writing down bank AT1s will=
 have huge consequences for the economy. Still it is=C2=A0<em>kind=C2=A0</e=
m>of right. You want the people who=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>bear the risk of=
 bank failures to=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to bear the risk, and then, when =
a bank fails, you want them to actually bear the risk.</p>
