<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s additional tier 1=
 capital securities were zeroed in March, its subordinated bonds were not. =
The subordinated bonds were fine, they are still outstanding, and Credit Su=
isse (which is being acquired by UBS Group AG) is still paying them. Intuit=
ively, the way to describe this is something like =E2=80=9Cthe subordinated=
 bonds are senior to the AT1s, so the subordinated bonds get paid before th=
e AT1s do.=E2=80=9D And in fact it was and is fairly standard to describe t=
he capital structure of Credit Suisse =E2=80=94=C2=A0or any other big Europ=
ean bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0by saying that AT1s are below subordinated bonds, w=
hich are below senior unsecured bonds, etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are credit default swaps outstanding on =
Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s subordinated bonds. These swaps would be triggered,=
 and would pay off, if the subordinated bonds were written down, but those =
bonds were not written down. They would also be triggered, though, if any C=
redit Suisse bonds that are =E2=80=9Cnot subordinated to=E2=80=9D those bon=
ds were written down. The AT1s were written down. Were the AT1s =E2=80=9Cno=
t subordinated to=E2=80=9D the subordinated bonds? Obviously they were subo=
rdinated, in a practical=C2=A0sense =E2=80=94 they were written down and th=
e bonds were not!=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the documents are a little ambigu=
ous and these things thrive on technicalities, so some hedge funds bought C=
DS on the sub bonds and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31513959.263431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
